@PaulSD actually, the `drop()` function is the complement to `begin()`, that called implicitly on the first change. Both operate on transactions — `begin()` creates one, while `drop()` drops the transaction object. And `remove()` is the complement to `add()`. These two operate on objects in the DB. While `commit()` applies a transaction to an object in the DB.

Probably there is a reason to remove a newly created DB object, though it would be a model violation.

And it's a good idea to automatically clean up all the failed objects by some call. Thanks, will try to implement it.

