Hey Abed!

Sorry, the documentation isn't super clear on this. The extended facts are not visible by default in the html_fancy template, except for the "dtap", "comment" and other custom variables. The idea with extended facts is that you can add facts missing from Ansible's generated facts. For example, Ansible reports no memory for certain BSD machines, so you could add them manually in an extended variables file.

For now, if you want your extended facts to show up in the output, you can either modify the template or abuse the fact that the html_fancy template displays "host local facts" by putting the extended information in the `ansible_facts` -> `ansible_local` key:

    {
      "ansible_facts": {
        "ansible_local": {
          "software": [
            "Apache2",
            "MySQL5.5"
          ]
      }
    }

I'm going to implement a new section in the `html_fancy` template specifically for displaying custom facts.

@ebreton Thanks a lot for your contributions, however I think handling the multiple results (even all results) should be stored as GeoJSON Point FeatureCollection.

http://geojson.org/

- [ ] All providers should return a FeatureCollection regardless if it's 1 result or multiple results.
- [ ] Custom properties from providers should be stored in each individual GeoJSON Point `properties`.

```json
{
  "type": "FeatureCollection",
  "features": [
    {
      "type": "Feature",
      "properties": {},
      "geometry": {
        "type": "Point",
        "coordinates": [
          39.7265625,
          35.17380831799959
        ]
      }
    },
    {
      "type": "Feature",
      "properties": {},
      "geometry": {
        "type": "Point",
        "coordinates": [
          21.09375,
          54.57206165565852
        ]
      }
    }
  ]
}
```

