After reflecting on this, the obvious candidate to act as a property-like accessor is the `serializable`. It already handles getting, so all we need to do is modify the "extended serializable" plan a bit:


```python
    @serializable
    class full_name:

        def serialize(self):
            return '%s %s' % (self.first_name, self.last_name)

        def deserialize(self, value):
            self.first_name, self.last_name = value.split()
```

So, instead of returning a dictionary, the deserializer method simply sets the attributes directly on the instance. This is actually a much cleaner solution, and now the setter can be invoked at any time. The import machinery just needs to create a dummy instance on which the setter operates, since the final object doesn't yet exist at that point, but other than that I don't foresee any complexities here.

By the way, I should mention that there's no technical reason (I think...) why the two functions should be enclosed within a class construct. It's also possible to opt for a more canonical syntax:

```python

    @serializable
    def full_name(self):
        return '%s %s' % (self.first_name, self.last_name)

    @full_name.setter
    def full_name(self, value):
        self.first_name, self.last_name = value.split()
```

There are endless ways to name the second decorator; the only requirement is that we need a reference to the main serializable, either as the decorator object or its parameter. For example:

```python
    serializable.set(full_name)
    def full_name(self, value):
        ...
```

