If you create an actor with no arguments in the decorator, e.g.,

```python
@ray.remote
class Foo:
    def method(self):
        ...
```

Then you can create an actor with `f = Foo.remote()` and it won't require any resources for its lifetime. However, each method invocation, e.g.,`f.method.remote()` will require 1 CPU resource.

In contrast, if you do

```python
@ray.remote(num_cpus=1)
class Foo:
    def method(self):
        ...
```

then the actor will reserve 1 CPU resource for its entire lifetime, and method invocations will not require any additional resources.

